{"title_page": "Charles H. Porter", "text_new": "{{for|the mayor of Quincy, Massachusetts|Charles H. Porter (mayor)}}\n<!-- This article was automatically created by [[User:polbot]] from http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=P000438. The prose may be stilted, and there may be grammatical and Wikification errors. Please improve in any way you see fit. -->\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name                = Charles Howell Porter\n|image = CharlesHPorter.jpg\n|state = [[Virginia]]\n|district = [[Virginia's 3rd congressional district|3rd]]\n|term_start = January 26, 1870\n|term_end = March 3, 1873\n|predecessor = [[Daniel Coleman DeJarnette, Sr.|Daniel C. DeJarnette]] (1861)\n|successor = [[John Ambler Smith|John A. Smith]]\n|birth_date         = June 21, 1833\n|birth_place        = [[Cairo, New York]]\n|death_date         = {{death date and age|1897|7|9|1833|6|21|mf=y}}\n|death_place        = Cairo, New York\n|resting_place = Cairo Cemetery, Cairo, New York\n|party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|profession = [[lawyer]]\n|alma_mater = [[Albany Law School]]\n|battles = [[American Civil War]]\n|branch = [[Union Army]]\n|allegiance = [[United States of America]]\n|unit = [[1st Regiment New York Mounted Rifles]]\n}}\n'''Charles Howell Porter''' (June 21, 1833 &ndash; July 9, 1897) was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Virginia]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Cairo, New York]], Porter completed preparatory studies.\nHe was graduated from the law university at [[Albany, New York]], in 1853.\nHe was admitted to the bar in 1854 and commenced practice in [[Ashland, Greene County, New York|Ashland, New York]].\nHe entered the [[Union Army]] in 1861 as a member of the [[1st Regiment New York Mounted Rifles]].\nHe settled in [[Norfolk, Virginia]].\nHe served as city attorney for one year.\n<!-- A grammar fix may be needed here. -->Commonwealth attorney 1863\u20131867.\nHe moved to [[Richmond, Virginia]], in 1867.\n\nHe served as member of the [[Virginia Constitutional Convention of 1868]].\n<!-- A grammar fix may be needed here. -->Upon the readmission of Virginia to representation was elected as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to the Forty-first and Forty-second Congresses and served from January 26, 1870, to March 3, 1873.\nHe declined to be a candidate for renomination in 1872.\nHe engaged in the practice of law in New York City and Beacon, New York.\nHe died in Cairo, New York, July 9, 1897.\nHe was interred in Cairo Cemetery.\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n*'''1869'''; Porter was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives with 77.16% of the vote, defeating Independents James W. Hunnicutt and John E. Mulford.\n*'''1870'''; Porter was re-elected unopposed.\n\n==References==\n{{CongBio|P000438}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{Find a Grave|7742089}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Virginia\n| district=3\n| before=[[Daniel Coleman DeJarnette, Sr.|Daniel C. DeJarnette]] (1861)\n| after=[[John Ambler Smith|John A. Smith]]\n| years=1870\u20131873}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{VirginiaRepresentatives03}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Porter, Charles Howell}}\n[[Category:1833 births]]\n[[Category:1897 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Virginia Republicans]]\n[[Category:Union Army personnel]]\n[[Category:People of New York (state) in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People from Cairo, New York]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n\n{{Virginia-Representative-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the mayor of Quincy, Massachusetts|Charles H. Porter (mayor)}}\n<!-- This article was automatically created by [[User:polbot]] from http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=P000438. The prose may be stilted, and there may be grammatical and Wikification errors. Please improve in any way you see fit. -->\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name                = Charles Howell Porter\n|image = CharlesHPorter.jpg\n|state = [[Virginia]]\n|district = [[Virginia's 3rd congressional district|3rd]]\n|term_start = January 26, 1870\n|term_end = March 3, 1873\n|predecessor = [[Daniel Coleman DeJarnette, Sr.|Daniel C. DeJarnette]] (1861)\n|successor = [[John Ambler Smith|John A. Smith]]\n|birth_date         = June 21, 1833\n|birth_place        = [[Cairo, New York]]\n|death_date         = {{death date and age|1897|7|9|1833|6|21|mf=y}}\n|death_place        = Cairo, New York\n|resting_place = Cairo Cemetery, Cairo, New York\n|party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|profession = [[lawyer]]\n|alma_mater = [[Albany Law School]]\n|battles = [[American Civil War]]\n|branch = [[Union Army]]\n|allegiance = [[United States of America]]\n|unit = [[1st Regiment New York Mounted Rifles]]\n}}\n'''Charles Howell Porter''' (June 21, 1833 &ndash; July 9, 1897) was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Virginia]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Cairo, New York]], Porter completed preparatory studies.\nHe was graduated from the law university at [[Albany, New York]], in 1853.\nHe was admitted to the bar in 1854 and commenced practice in [[Ashland, Greene County, New York|Ashland, New York]].\nHe entered the [[Union Army]] in 1861 as a member of the [[1st Regiment New York Mounted Rifles]].\nHe settled in [[Norfolk, Virginia]].\nHe served as city attorney for one year.\n<!-- A grammar fix may be needed here. -->Commonwealth attorney 1863-1867.\nHe moved to [[Richmond, Virginia]], in 1867.\n\nHe served as member of the [[Virginia Constitutional Convention of 1868]].\n<!-- A grammar fix may be needed here. -->Upon the readmission of Virginia to representation was elected as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to the Forty-first and Forty-second Congresses and served from January 26, 1870, to March 3, 1873.\nHe declined to be a candidate for renomination in 1872.\nHe engaged in the practice of law in New York City and Beacon, New York.\nHe died in Cairo, New York, July 9, 1897.\nHe was interred in Cairo Cemetery.\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n*'''1869'''; Porter was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives with 77.16% of the vote, defeating Independents James W. Hunnicutt and John E. Mulford.\n*'''1870'''; Porter was re-elected unopposed.\n\n==References==\n{{CongBio|P000438}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{Find a Grave|7742089}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Virginia\n| district=3\n| before=[[Daniel Coleman DeJarnette, Sr.|Daniel C. DeJarnette]] (1861)\n| after=[[John Ambler Smith|John A. Smith]]\n| years=1870\u20131873}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{VirginiaRepresentatives03}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Porter, Charles Howell}}\n[[Category:1833 births]]\n[[Category:1897 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Virginia Republicans]]\n[[Category:Union Army personnel]]\n[[Category:People of New York (state) in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People from Cairo, New York]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n\n{{Virginia-Representative-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1863-1867 \u2192 1863\u20131867", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_H._Porter"}
{"title_page": "Mostafa Zamani", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mostafa Zamani\n| image              = Mostafazamani.png\n| caption            = Mostafa Zamani\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1982|06|20}}\n| birth_place        = [[Amlash]], [[Gilan]], [[Iran]]\n| yearsactive        = 2005\u2013present\n| occupation         = [[Actor]]\n| education          = [[Islamic Azad University]] \u2013 Master of Technology Management\n| relatives          = \n| signature          = \n}}\n'''Mostafa Zamani''' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u0635\u0637\u0641\u06cc \u0632\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc}}; born 20 june 1982) is an [[Iran]]ian actor.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.tehrantimes.com/news/411576/Iranian-movie-theaters-to-refresh-schedules-for-Noruz|title= Iranian movie theaters to refresh schedules for Noruz |date= March 3, 2017|newspaper= [[Tehran Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Mostafa Zamani\">{{cite web|last=Zamani|first=Mostafa|title=Mostafa Zamani biography|url=http://www.whatsupiran.com/Profile/Mostafa-Zamani/About|work=actor|publisher=http://www.whatsupiran.com|accessdate=6 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928063054/http://www.whatsupiran.com/Profile/Mostafa-Zamani/About|archive-date=28 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://waleg.com/archives/018124.html|title= The Mesmerizing Mostafa Zamani|date= November 19, 2009|website= waleg.com}}</ref> He was born from [[Mazanderani people|Mazandrani]] father and [[Gilak people|Gilani]] mother at [[Gilan]] and he lived until 7 years old at Gilan and then he moved to [[Fereydunkenar]] [[Mazandaran Province]].<ref>[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=gOhLFrGiWbg Mostafa Zamani, according to his interview youtube source ]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMostafa Zamani obtained an Industrial Management degree before earning a master's degree in Technology Management.\n\nHe made his series debut in 2008 with ''[[Prophet Joseph (TV series)|Prophet Joseph]]'' which gained him popular acclaim.\n\nHe has acted in a number of series such as ''In the Eye of the Storm'' (2003\u20132009) and ''Shahrzad'' (2015\u20132018).\n\nZamani made his cinematic debut in 2009 with ''Aul''.\n\nSince then, he has appeared in a number of movies, including ''Farewell Baghdad'' (2009), ''Retribution'' (2009), ''Parya's Story'' (2010), ''Parinaz'' (2010), ''The Final Whistle'' (2010), ''A Simple Romance'' (2011), ''The Queen'' (2011), ''I'm Her Spouse'' (2011), ''Berlin 7'' (2011), ''Mirror and Candlestick'' (2012) and ''The Exclusive Line'' (2013).\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2008 || ''[[Prophet Joseph (TV series)|Prophet Joseph]]'' || [[Joseph in Islam|Joseph]] || [[IRIB TV1]]\n|-\n| ''[[Dar Cheshm-e Baad]]'' || Guest  || [[IRIB TV1]]\n|-\n| 2015\u20132018 || ''[[Shahrzad (TV series)|Shahrzad]]''<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.tehrantimes.com/news/252923/Producer-takes-Shahrzad-to-European-Film-Market|title= Producer takes \"Shahrzad\" to European Film Market|date= February 13, 2016|newspaper= [[Tehran Times]]}}</ref> || Farhad Damavandi || Film Net \n|-\n| 2018 || ''Prophet Moses'' || Joseph ||[[IRIB TV1]]\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Blue Whale (series)|Blue Whale]]\n|Jahan\n|[[Home video]] in Iran\n|}\n\n===Movies===\n\n*[[A Special Day (2016)]]\n*Atena (2015)\n*Small Black Fish (2014)\n*Jame Daran (2014)\n*Special Line (2014)\n*Twenty Weeks (2013)\n*Mirror Shmdvn (2013)\n*Berlin -7 (2012)\n*South Street Thief (2012)\n*I am his wife (2012)\n*My Father Love Story (2012)\n*Queen (2012)\n*A simple romantic (2011)\n*Final whistle (2011)\n*Parinaz (2011)\n*Booye Gandom (2010)\n*Paria Story (2009)\n*Penalty (2009)\n*Goodbye Baghdad (2009)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat|Mostafa Zamani}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140109052216/http://www.whatsupiran.com/Profile/Mostafa-Zamani Mostafa Zamani