9-11-19}}</ref> Oz was a guest on [[CNBC]] ''[[Squawk Box]]'' on December 23, 2015 and again on December 26, 2018. He returned to ''Squawk Box'' and aired again on December 27, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://video.cnbc.com/gallery/?video=3000466084|title=Wall Street's mentalist shows his magic|website=CNBC|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Mentalist Oz Pearlman shows off his CNBC 2019 Stock Draft 'advantage'|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S8vTuZ0EcTA|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> Pearlman appeared on The Dr. Oz Show on December 20, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.doctoroz.com/episode/how-you-can-tap-your-subconscious-mind-heal-your-body?video_id=5254086304001|title=Oz Pearlman Tricks Dr. Oz|access-date=2017-02-03}}</ref> Oz was aired on Episode 7 of the Bravo TV series ''[[Million Dollar Listing]]'' on September 12, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bravotv.com/million-dollar-listing-new-york/season-8/ep-7-polar-opposites|title=Ep 7: Polar Opposites|date=2019-09-05|website=Bravo TV Official Site|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref> Oz was aired on the CNBC show ''[[Power Lunch]]'' in 2018 and twice in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/video/2018/05/11/mentalist-oz-pearlman-demonstrates-magic-of-picking-stocks.html|title=Mentalist Oz Pearlman demonstrates 'magic' of picking stocks|date=2018-05-11|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/14/mentalist-oz-pearlman-is-betting-bitcoin-will-hit-12000-by-next-year.html|title=CNBC Stock Draft contestant Oz Pearlman is betting bitcoin will hit $12,000 by next year|last=Fox|first=Michelle|date=2019-05-14|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Mentalist Oz Pearlman shows off his CNBC 2019 Stock Draft 'advantage'|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S8vTuZ0EcTA|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> He appeared on [[ABC World News Tonight]] on July 24, 2009. Oz made a guest appearance on [[CBS]]\u2019s ''[[The Early Show|Early Show]]'' on May 30, 2009. Pearlman appeared on [[ESPN]] in 2017, 2018, and 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/video/clip/_/id/22740369|title=Mentalist amazes Melrose - ESPN Video|date=2018-03-13|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/video/clip/_/id/22737873|title=Mentalist mystifies Beadle, Jalen with bracket tricks - ESPN Video|date=2018-03-13|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/video/clip/_/id/23001324|title=Oz The Mentalist predicts Villanova blows out Michigan - ESPN Video|date=2018-04-02|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/video/clip/_/id/18904777|title=Sleep deprived Jay Williams gets mental test - ESPN Video|date=2017-03-14|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref> He appeared as a guest at ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]''{{'}}s studio on April 7, 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/video/mentalist-oz-pearlman-brings-mind-bending-magic-to-lunch-break/|title=Mentalist Oz Pearlman Brings Mind-Bending Magic to Lunch Break|last=|first=|date=April 7, 2016|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=April 10, 2016|via=}}</ref> [[InStyle]] (the global fashion magazine publisher) released a video of Oz performing as a guest in 2017.<ref>{{Citation|title=Prepare to be amazed by Mentalist Oz Pearlman|url=https://www.facebook.com/InStyle/videos/10156009224849985/|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> Pearlman was featured on a commercial for ''[[Mohegan Sun]]'' in China.<ref name=\"ozpearlman.com\"/> Pearlman was a guest on the national radio show ''[[Elvis Duran and the Morning Show]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.downtownflemington.com/pub/gen/event/25568/fulltext|title=Spring Cultural Series: Oz Pearlman, Mentalist & Magician|website=m.downtownflemington.com|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref> As an athlete, he won the Chicago Ultra Marathon when he completed the 50-mile marathon in 5 hours, 25 minutes, and 26 seconds.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/nyc-magician-oz-perlman-wins-long-island-marathon-1.10375737|title=NYC magician Oz Pearlman wins LI Marathon|website=Newsday|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\n=== Early life ===\nOz Pearlman was born on July 19, [[1982]] in [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thementalismcourse.com/how-much-is-oz-pearlman-worth-oz-pearlman-net-worth/|title=Who is Oz Pearlman?|author=[https://thementalismcourse.com/author/russell/ Russell]|website=thementalismcourse.com|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Three years later, he moved to the United States. His father\u2019s reason for moving was to pursue an engineering job. Oz participated in sports such as soccer and swimming. Oz read works of science fiction and attended summer camp at the Wisconsin Center for Academically Talented Youth. When Pearlman was only 12 years old, he achieved a score of 800 for the area of mathematics when he completed his [[SAT]]s.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tabletmag.com/jewish-arts-and-culture/theater-and-dance/137298/oz-pearlman-magician-marathoner|title=Oz Pearlman, the Next Great Jewish Magician?|website=Tablet Magazine|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref>\n\n=== University education ===\nPearlman earned a bachelor\u2019s degree in electrical engineering from the [[University of Michigan]] in 2003. He began at the university when he was 16 years old. Income earned from performing magic at restaurants, kids\u2019 shows, and corporate events starting at age 14 (2 years prior to his enrollment) funded his college tuition there. He said he always had a deck of cards on him between the ages of 13 and 18.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eecs.umich.edu/eecs/about/articles/2015/an-engineers-magic-moment.html|title=An Engineer's Magic Moment {{!}} Electrical and Computer Engineering (ECE) @ Michigan|website=www.eecs.umich.edu|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2013/06/ultramarathon-running-magician|title=Ultramarathon running magician has 135 mile race up his sleeve|website=For The Win|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref>\n\n=== Award-winning Marathon athlete ===\nOz Pearlman won the [[New Jersey Marathon]] four times. He ranks within the top 30 fastest Americans for 50-mile races. His current top record was set when he ran 50 miles in 5 hours, 25 minutes, and 26 seconds; this accomplishment established him as the 1st Place winner of the Chicago Ultra Marathon (Chicago Lakefront) in 2009.<ref name=\":0\" /> Other races in which he has participated include [[Ironman World Championship|Hawaii Ironman World Championship]], Western States 100 Mile Run, Spartathlon 153 Mile Run, Leadville 100 Mile Run, and Badwater 135 Mile Run.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://heavy.com/entertainment/2015/09/oz-pearlman-agt-winner-americas-got-talent-mentalist-2015-finale-season-10/6/|title=Oz Pearlman \u2013 The Mentalist on \u2018America\u2019s Got Talent\u2019 2015 Finale|last=Weigle|first=Lauren|website=Heavy.com|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref>\n\n== Press coverage ==\nOn August 7, 2019, ''[[New York Post]]'' published an article on Oz that was titled \"Magician Oz Pearlman snaps up $4.5M Brooklyn penthouse\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/07/magician-oz-pearlman-snaps-up-4-5m-brooklyn-penthouse/|title=Magician Oz Pearlman snaps up $4.5M Brooklyn penthouse|last=Keil|first=Jennifer Gould|date=2019-08-07|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\nOn June 14, 2018, ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' published an article about Oz that was titled \"Famed Mentalist Oz Pearlman Leaves Crossover TV in Shock\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2018/06/14/famed-mentalist-oz-pearlman-leaves-crossover-tv-shock|title=Mentalist Oz Pearlman Leaves Crossover TV In Shock|last=Staff|first=S. I.|website=Sports Illustrated|language=en-us|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\nOn October 19, 2017, ''[[New York Post]]'' published an article about Pearlman titled \"This mentalist specializes in freaking out celebrities\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2017/10/19/this-mentalist-specializes-in-freaking-out-celebrities/|title=This mentalist specializes in freaking out celebrities|last=Kaplan|first=Michael|date=2017-10-19|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n\nOn October 5, 2019, [[Entrepreneur (magazine)|''Entrepreneur'']] released an article titled \"Want to Reach Your Goals? Adopt and Embrace \" that mentioned Oz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/251178|title=Want to Reach Your Goals? Adopt and Embrace the Hustle Mentality.|last=Patel|first=Sujan|date=2015-10-05|website=Entrepreneur|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\nOn February 21, 2016, Pearlman was featured in the Leadership section of [[Forbes]]. The article was titled \"5 Ways Your Body Language Give You Away: A Famed Mentalist Shares His Secrets\". Techniques of [[nonverbal communication]] Oz applied during television appearances and corporate event entertainment were disclosed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kathycaprino/2016/02/21/5-ways-your-body-language-gives-you-away-a-famed-mentalist-shares-his-secrets/|title=5 Ways Your Body Language Gives You Away: A Famed Mentalist Shares His Secrets|website=Forbes|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn August 5, 2015, Pearlman was featured in an article by ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' called \"The Art of Hustling: America\u2019s Got Talent star mentalist on goals and persistence\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-p-owens/the-art-of-hustling-ameri_b_8034210.html|title=The Art of Hustling: America's Got Talent's star mentalist on goals and persistence|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, 2015, ''[[Forbes]]'' published an article on Pearlman titled \"Mastering Illusions of the Mind\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/joshwolfe/2015/03/30/mastering-illusions-of-the-mind/|title=Mastering Illusions Of The Mind|website=Forbes|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref>\n\nPearlman was featured in a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' article titled \"Oz, The Great Wizard\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ozpearlman.com/gallery/press/02.jpg|title=Oz, The Great Wizard|last=|first=|date=|work=New York Times|access-date=|via=}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2013, Pearlman was featured in an article published by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/vault/2013/07/01/106339902/oz-great-and-tired|title=Oz, Great And Tired|last=Bechtel|first=Mark|website=SI.com|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2004, Pearlman was featured in an article by ''[[New York Post]]'' titled \"Do You Believe in Magic?\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2004/03/20/do-you-believe-in-magic/|title=Do You Believe in Magic?|last=Hoffman|first=Barbara|website=New York Post|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn June 7, 2013, ''[[USA Today]]'' featured an article on Oz Pearlman called \"Ultramarathon running magician has 135 mile race up his sleeve\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Performances ==\nOz performed for a number of C-level executives; these associations eventually inspired his transition from a part-time entertainer to a full-time entertainer. After Pearlman performed for [[Jeffrey R. Immelt|Jeffery Immelt]], Chairman and CEO of [[General Electric]], Immelt responded, \u201cHe just turned one dollar bills into hundreds. Amazing!\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://2paragraphs.com/2015/08/oz-pearlman-turns-dollar-bills-into-hundreds-for-wall-street-ceos/|title=Oz Pearlman Turns Dollar Bills Into Hundreds for Wall Street CEOs|website=2Paragraphs.com|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-28}}</ref> [[James P. Gorman]], the current CEO of [[Morgan Stanley]], was working at [[Merrill Lynch]] when Pearlman was hired to deliver a [[corporate entertainment]] show for the senior management of the company. This event was later described by Oz as the experience that sparked his transition from a day job employee to full-time entertainer.\n\n== Transition to full-time entertainer ==\nPearlman was employed at Merrill Lynch in the company's global technology services department and performing magic and mentalism as a part-time profession. The company hired him to deliver event entertainment to upper management within the company. James Gorman, who experienced the entertainment, asked Pearlman what he is doing as a regular employee at the company (implying the business entertainment was good enough to not need a day job). Two months later, Oz quit the day job at Merrill Lynch and became a full-time entertainer.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Teaching ==\nIn 2003 Pearlman created an instructional DVD called ''Born to Perform Card Magic'' that teaches techniques of magic. The filming for the DVD took place in [[Las Vegas]]. The DVD sold over 100,000 copies. The ratings were among the highest in the history of the magic supplier selling the DVDs.<ref name=\":1\" /> An expanded and updated version of the DVD was produced in 2013, which was completely re-filmed and features twice the length of video footage.<ref>[https://www.themagiccafe.com/forums/viewtopic.php?topic=656860 \"Oz Pearlman's updated and expanded Born to Perform Card Magic DVD (2013)\"]. 4 January 2018.  Retrieved 31 January 2020.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|3878582}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pearlman, Oz}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan College of Engineering alumni]]\n[[Category:Mentalists]]\n[[Category:Israeli magicians]]\n[[Category:Merrill Lynch people]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced:1982\u2192 1982", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oz_Pearlman"}
{"title_page": "Suwanda H. J. Sugunasiri", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2017}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|biography|date=January 2017}}\n{{notability|biography|date=January 2017}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = [[Professor]] Suwanda H. J. Sugunasiri\n| image       =\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = 1936\n| birth_place = [[Tangalle]] [[Sri Lanka]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence   = [[Toronto]], Canada\n| nationality =  Canadian\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = Novelist, poet and scholar \n| education   = [[Nalanda College Colombo]], [[Ananda College]], [[Vidyalankara University]], [[University of London]], [[University of Pennsylvania]], [[University of Toronto]]\n| employer    = \n| occupation  = [[Professor]]\n| title       = \n| networth    = \n| height      = \n| weight      = \n| term        = \n| predecessor =   \n| successor   = \n| party       = \n| boards      = \n| spouse      = \n| partner     = \n| children    = \n| parents     = \n| relatives   = \n| signature   = \n| website     = \n| footnotes   = \n}}\n\n'''Suwanda H. J. Sugunasiri''' (known as Suwanda Sugunasiri) is a Canadian academic, educator, author, journalist and poet.  He is a former education [[professor]] at the [[University of Ontario]] in [[Oshawa]], [[Ontario]], and the founder of the now-defunct Nalanda College of Buddhist Studies (Canada) in [[Toronto]].\n\n==Early childhood and education==\n\nSugunasiri was born to Buddhist parents in [[Tangalle]], [[Sri Lanka]], and educated at [[Nalanda College Colombo]] and [[Ananda College]] in [[Colombo]]. While at Nalanda he was active in sports, serving as vice-captain of an under-16 team, and also a lance-sergeant of a junior cadet platoon at Nalanda.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nAlthough he failed to gain admission to [[University of Ceylon]], Sugunasiri earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from [[University of London]] through self-study, specializing in the [[Pali]], [[Sanskrit]] and [[Sinhalese language|Sinhala]] languages.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nIn 1964 he earned a [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright]] Smith Mundt scholarship from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in the United States.\n\nSugunasiri also holds a master's degree in [[linguistics]] from the [[University of Pennsylvania]], and two master's degrees in [[moral philosophy]], and scientific study of religion and [[Buddhism]] from the [[University of Toronto]]. He was awarded a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] in national development by the [[Ontario Institute for Studies in Education]] at the University of Toronto.<ref>[http://buddhistcouncil.ca/bios.html Buddhist Council of Canada: Bios PROF. SUWANDA H. J. SUGUNASIRI]</ref>\n\n==Later life==\n\nSugunasiri is also the founder of Nalanda College of Buddhist Studies (Canada), and served as its president in the early 2000s.<ref>[http://archives.dailynews.lk/2011/06/29/art06.asp Real and imaginary homelands]</ref>\n\nHe was a columnist at the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' from 1993 to 1998. He was the president of the Buddhist Council of Canada until January 1, 2019, when he was replaced by Ven. Bhikkhu Mihita.<ref>[http://buddhistcouncil.ca/files/BCC-PRESS-RELEASE-BCC-Revived-Jan-01-2019.pdf Buddhist Council of Canada Revived]</ref>\n\nHe has authored numerous books in Buddhism, South-Asian Canadian literature, and Canadian multiculturalism.  He also wrote [[fiction]] and [[poetry]].{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2011/04/07/fea21.asp\n|title=Cricket: A civilized and happy sport \n|date= 7 April 2011\n|publisher=Dailynews\n|accessdate=22 May 2014}}\n* {{cite web\n |url          = http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2011/06/26/mon30.asp\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110704121745/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2011/06/26/mon30.asp\n |url-status = dead|archive-date = 4 July 2011\n |title        = Slice of life: complex or complicated?\n |date         = 2011-06-26\n |publisher    = Dailynews\n |accessdate   = 22 May 2014\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |url          = http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2003/01/12/fea11.html\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20030118015440/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2003/01/12/fea11.html\n |url-status = dead|archive-date = 18 January 2003\n |title        = Musings of a ghost from the past : Random thoughts on Prof. Sucarita Gamlath\n |date         = 2003-01-12\n |publisher    = Sunday Observer\n |accessdate   = 22 May 2014\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g7b5X7c-vCs\n|title=Arahant Mahinda - Redactor of the Buddhapujava in Sinhala Buddhist\n|date= Mar 24, 2013\n|publisher=youtube\n|accessdate=22 May 2014}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.lankaweb.com/news/items04/050704-3.html\n|title=NALANDA - CANADA'S FIRST BUDDHIST COLLEGE\n|date=\n|publisher=Lankaweb\n|accessdate=2014}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.lankaweb.com/news/items/2015/03/01/triune-mind-in-buddhism/\n|title=Triune Mind in Buddhism\n|date= 1 March 2015\n|publisher=Lankaweb\n|accessdate=2015}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sugunasiri, Suwanda}}\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese academics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Nalanda College, Colombo]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan novelists]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan poets]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Sri Lankan descent]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan expatriate academics]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian Buddhists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Buddhists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Buddhist poets]]\n[[Category:Buddhist writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2017}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|biography|date=January 2017}}\n{{notability|biography|date=January 2017}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = [[Professor]] Suwanda H. J. Sugunasiri\n| image       =\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = 1936\n| birth_place = [[Tangalle]] [[Sri Lanka]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence   = [[Toronto]], Canada\n| nationality =  Canadian\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = Novelist, poet and scholar \n| education   = [[Nalanda College Colombo]], [[Ananda College]], [[Vidyalankara University]], [[University of London]], [[University of Pennsylvania]], [[University of Toronto]]\n| employer    = \n| occupation  = [[Professor]]\n| title       = \n| networth    = \n| height      = \n| weight      = \n| term        = \n| predecessor =   \n| successor   = \n| party       = \n| boards      = \n| spouse      = \n| partner     = \n| children    = \n| parents     = \n| relatives   = \n| signature   = \n| website     = \n| footnotes   = \n}}\n\n'''Suwanda H. J. Sugunasiri''' (known as Suwanda Sugunasiri) is a Canadian academic, educator, author, journalist and poet.  He is a former education [[professor]] at the [[University of Ontario]] in [[Oshawa]], [[Ontario]], and the founder of the now-defunct Nalanda College of Buddhist Studies (Canada) in [[Toronto]].\n\n==Early childhood and education==\n\nSugunasiri was born to Buddhist parents in [[Tangalle]], [[Sri Lanka]], and educated at [[Nalanda College Colombo]] and [[Ananda College]] in [[Colombo]]. While at Nalanda he was active in sports, serving as vice-captain of an under-16 team, and also a lance-sergeant of a junior cadet platoon at Nalanda.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nAlthough he failed to gain admission to [[University of Ceylon]], Sugunasiri earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from [[University of London]] through self-study, specializing in the [[Pali]], [[Sanskrit]] and [[Sinhalese language|Sinhala]] languages.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nIn 1964 he earned a [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright]] Smith Mundt scholarship from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in the United States.\n\nSugunasiri also holds a master's degree in [[linguistics]] from the [[University of Pennsylvania]], and two master's degrees in [[moral philosophy]], and scientific study of religion and [[Buddhism]] from the [[University of Toronto]]. He was awarded a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] in national development by the [[Ontario Institute for Studies in Education]] at the University of Toronto.<ref>[http://buddhistcouncil.ca/bios.html Buddhist Council of Canada: Bios PROF. SUWANDA H. J. SUGUNASIRI]</ref>\n\n==Later life==\n\nSugunasiri is also the founder of Nalanda College of Buddhist Studies (Canada), and served as its president in the early 2000s.<ref>[http://archives.dailynews.lk/2011/06/29/art06.asp Real and imaginary homelands]</ref>\n\nHe was a columnist at the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' from 1993 to 1998. He was the president of the Buddhist Council of Canada until January 1, 2019, when he was replaced by Ven. Bhikkhu Mihita.<ref>[http://buddhistcouncil.ca/files/BCC-PRESS-RELEASE-BCC-Revived-Jan-01-2019.pdf Buddhist Council of Canada Revived]</ref>\n\nHe has authored numerous books in Buddhism, South-Asian Canadian literature, and Canadian multiculturalism.  He also wrote [[fiction]] and [[poetry]].{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2011/04/07/fea21.asp\n|title=Cricket: A civilized and happy sport \n|date= 7 April 2011\n|publisher=Dailynews\n|accessdate=22 May 2014}}\n* {{cite web\n |url          = http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2011/06/26/mon30.asp\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110704121745/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2011/06/26/mon30.asp\n |url-status = dead|archive-date = 4 July 2011\n |title        = Slice of life: complex or complicated?\n |date         = 2011-06-26\n |